07902nam a22010815i 9789814843478DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20192019si     fo  d z      eng d  a2019353440  a97898148434787 a10.1355/97898148434782doi  a(DE-B1597)534707  a(OCoLC)1110715334  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG00aDS631b.I53 2019 7aSOC0200002bisacsh04a305.8009222/ger00aContentious Belonging :bThe Place of Minorities in Indonesia /ced. by Greg Fealy, Ronit Ricci. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (282 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables and figures -- tContributors -- tAcknowledgments -- tGlossary -- t1. Diversity and its discontents: an overview of minority–majority relations in Indonesia -- tPART 1. HISTORY AND LAW -- t2. Minorities in Indonesian history: from ambiguous advantage to cantonisation -- t3. Minorities and discrimination in Indonesia: the legal framework -- t4. The Constitutional Court and minority rights: analysing the recent homosexual sex and indigenous belief cases -- tPART 2. DISABILITY -- t5. Changing laws, changing attitudes: the place of people with disability in Indonesia -- t6. Disability inclusion in Indonesia: the role of Islamic schools and universities in inclusive education reform -- tPART 3. SEXUALITY -- t7. Is the recent wave of homophobia in Indonesia unexpected? -- t8. Localising queer identities: queer activisms and national belonging in Indonesia -- tPART 4. RELIGION AND ETHNICITY -- t9. The mobilisation of intolerance and its trajectories: Indonesian Muslims’ views of religious minorities and ethnic Chinese -- t10. Disputes over places of worship in Indonesia: evaluating the role of the Interreligious Harmony Forum -- t11. Anti-Chinese sentiment and the ‘return’ of the pribumi discourse -- t12. Minority and advantage: the story of Sindhis in Indonesia -- t13. ‘Normalising’ the Orang Rimba: between mainstreaming, marginalising and respecting indigenous culture -- tPART 5. REFLECTIONS -- t14 Manipulating minorities and majorities: reflections on ‘contentious belonging’ -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aContention has surrounded the status of minorities throughout Indonesian history. Two broad polarities are evident: one inclusive of minorities, regarding them as part of the nation’s rich complexity and a manifestation of its “Unity in Diversity” motto; the other exclusive, viewing with suspicion or disdain those communities or groups that differ from the perceived majority. State and community attitudes towards minorities have fluctuated over time. Some periods have been notable for the acceptance of minorities and protection of their rights, while others have been marked by anti-minority discrimination, marginalisation and sometimes violence. This book explores the complex historical and contemporary dimensions of Indonesia’s religious, ethnic, LGBT and disability minorities from a range of perspectives, including historical, legal, political, cultural, discursive and social. It addresses fundamental questions about Indonesia’s tolerance and acceptance of difference, and examines the extent to which diversity is embraced or suppressed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aIndonesia -- Social conditions. 0aMinorities -- Civil rights -- Indonesia. 0aMinorities -- Indonesia. 0aMinoritiesxCivil rightszIndonesiavCongresses. 0aMinoritieszIndonesiavCongresses. 0aReligious tolerancezIndonesiavCongresses. 4aEthnic Studies. 4aMinority Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Minority Studies.2bisacsh1 aAfrianty, Dina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAli